</i></p><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-17_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Dental professionals hold a unique and critical role in maintaining public health in healthcare. The General Dental Council (GDC) serves as the regulatory body overseeing dental professionals in the United Kingdom, ensuring they meet the highest standards of practice. In this blog, Dr Richard Dune delves into the role of the GDC, highlighting its importance, key functions, and best practices for compliance with relevant legislation and regulations. </span>
</p></div></div></div></div></div><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Previous" class="pf-slider-prev none hide"></button><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Next" class="pf-slider-next none hide"></button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-2d75" data-category="Collection Suggestion" data-name="Tea" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-knuQPt cVHHwo pf-19_ pf-color-scheme-1"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-kRRxPL eBhmAi"><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-20_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-21_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-22_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key facts and statistics</h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-24_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The GDC regulates over 113,000 dental professionals, including dentists, nurses, and technicians. Established by the Dentists Act 1984, the GDC’s primary goal is to protect patient safety and maintain public confidence in dental services. According to the latest GDC report, in 2023, the council handled 3,450 fitness-to-practice cases, showcasing its pivotal role in maintaining professional standards.

</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-26_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-27_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-28_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions
</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kMriOJ brNffh pf-30_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bdOgOc bNKfVA pf-31_ pf-text-1"><strong>General Dental Council (GDC)</strong> - An independent organisation responsible for regulating dental professionals in the UK, ensuring they adhere to established standards.</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bdOgOc bNKfVA pf-33_ pf-text-1"><strong>Fitness to practise</strong> - The ability of a dental professional to perform their duties to the required standard without risk to patients or the public.&nbsp;</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bdOgOc bNKfVA pf-35_ pf-text-1"><strong>Continuing Professional Development (CPD) </strong>- Ongoing education and training that dental professionals must undertake to maintain registration and ensure their skills remain current.



</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-37_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-38_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-39_ pf-heading-1-h3">The role of the GDC</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-41_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Regulation and standards</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-43_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The GDC is mandated to establish and enforce dental education and practice standards. This includes setting the curriculum for dental training programmes and accrediting institutions that provide dental education. By doing so, the GDC ensures that all dental professionals receive consistent and high-quality training, equipping them with the skills and knowledge necessary to provide safe and effective care.

</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-45_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Registration and licensing</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-47_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Dental professionals must be registered with the GDC to practise legally in the UK. This registration process involves rigorous checks on qualifications, competence, and fitness to practise. The GDC maintains a public register of dental professionals, which patients can consult to verify the credentials of their dental care providers.


</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-49_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Fitness to practise</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-51_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Ensuring dental professionals remain fit to practise is a cornerstone of the GDC’s role. The council investigates complaints and conducts hearings to determine whether a professional’s conduct or competence falls below acceptable standards. Disciplinary actions can range from warnings and additional training requirements to suspension or removal from the register.



</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-53_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Continuing Professional Development (CPD)</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-55_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The GDC requires all registered dental professionals to undertake CPD activities. This continuous learning process helps professionals stay updated with advancements in dental care and maintain high standards of practice. Failure to meet CPD requirements can result in suspension or removal from the GDC register.


</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-57_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-58_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-59_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for compliance</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-61_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Understanding legislation and regulations</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-63_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Dental professionals must be well-versed in the legislative framework governing their practice. The Dentists Act 1984 and the GDC’s Standards for the Dental Team outline dental practitioners' legal and ethical obligations. Regular training and updates on these regulations are essential for maintaining compliance.

</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-65_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Implementing robust CPD programs</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-67_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Dental practices should implement structured CPD programmes to comply with the GDC’s CPD requirements. These programmes should cover a wide range of topics, including clinical skills, patient safety, and ethical practice. Platforms like ComplyPlus™ can streamline the management of CPD activities, ensuring all team members meet their requirements.


</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-69_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Maintaining high standards of patient care</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-71_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">The core of GDC’s standards is centred on patient care. Dental professionals should prioritise patient safety, dignity, and respect in all aspects of their practice. This includes obtaining informed consent, maintaining patient confidentiality, and providing treatments based on the best available evidence.




</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-73_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Regular audits and self-assessment</strong></h3><p class="sc-gFVuLS jpmtwg pf-75_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Conducting regular audits and self-assessments helps dental practices identify areas for improvement and ensure compliance with GDC standards. Practices should establish internal protocols for reviewing patient care, record-keeping, and adherence to professional guidelines.



</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-77_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-78_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-79_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kMriOJ brNffh pf-81_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bdOgOc bNKfVA pf-82_ pf-text-1"><strong>Utilising compliance management software </strong>- Investing in compliance management software like ComplyPlus™ can significantly enhance a dental practice’s ability to meet regulatory requirements. These tools provide a centralised platform for tracking CPD activities, managing patient records, and conducting internal audits, thereby ensuring ongoing compliance with GDC standards.
</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bdOgOc bNKfVA pf-84_ pf-text-1"><strong>Engaging in professional development </strong>- Encouraging a culture of continuous improvement and professional development within the dental team is crucial. Practices should support their staff in pursuing additional qualifications and specialisations, attending workshops, and participating in professional forums.



</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-dhKdPU hjOBND pf-86_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-iapVNj iUcVvL pf-87_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kAkozD kgiAhT pf-88_ pf-heading-1-h3">Conclusion
